@xujiegb Thanks for the clarification. I’m with you on the security risks, totally understand your concerns and the reasoning behind keeping things as they are.

Appreciate you taking the time to explain it and discuss the topic.
You guys are doing great work, and who knows, maybe lightning will strike in the near future with a safe new approach.

IIRC, v2rayN only requires the root privileges to
1. Create a tun interface and bind to it
2. Add routes to redirect traffic to the interface
3. Change DNS resolver address

The first and second requirements can be fullfilled by setting CAP_NET_ADMIN to the `~/.local/share/v2rayN/bin/sing_box/sing-box` binary
The third by creating a polkit rule that allows users to execute the following actions:
```
org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-domains
org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-default-route
org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-dns-servers
```
e.g.
```js
polkit.addRule(function(action,subject){
	if (
		(
			action.id=="org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-domains"||
			action.id=="org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-default-route"||
			action.id=="org.freedesktop.resolve1.set-dns-servers"
		) &&
		subject.isInGroup("v2rayn")
	)
	{
		returnpolkit.Result.YES;
	}
});
```
SELinux shouldn't be a problem because by default `~/.local/share/v2rayN/` is labeled as `unconfined_u:object_r:data_home_t:s0`

From the security standpoint this solution is much better than the proposal with a rootfull daemon as it completely prevents even the slightest chance of a privilege escalation attack.

However, it's still sub-optimal to give sing-box the CAP_NET_ADMIN capability which allows it perform various network-related operations, including those that we don't need for TUN:

```
•  administration of IP firewall, masquerading, and accounting;
•  set type-of-service (TOS);
•  clear driver statistics;
•  set promiscuous mode;
•  enabling multicasting;
•  use setsockopt(2) to set the following socket options: SO_DEBUG, SO_MARK, SO_PRIORITY (for a priority outside the range 0 to 6), SO_RCVBUFFORCE, and SO_SNDBUFFORCE.
```
One solution would be to use a separate sing-box binary with CAP_NET_ADMIN for TUN only. The binary must be restricted by a Mandatory Access Control system such as SELinux/AppArmor policy to TUN-related actions. This solution, however won't work on systems with a different MAC (TOMOYO, PARSEC, etc...) or on a system without any MAC at all. 

A different solution is to create a helper program that is only capable of setting up TUN for v2rayN and give it CAP_NET_ADMIN. The helper program must be write-protected (e.g. `chmod 0554; chown root:v2rayn`) and only executable by users authorized to run v2rayN in TUN mode. It's safe to add the default desktop user (uid 1000) to the v2rayn group during installation.

